 commutes, so that for m\in  Gz, f^*m = fm \in  Gz'. Thus the disjoint
  union of the Gz is a sieve. Conversely, given a sieve S, we
  define Gz = \{z\xrightarrow {m} x\in  C(z, x)\}, with action on morphisms by
  pre-composition.

A Grothendieck pretopology, or a basis for a Grothendieck topology, consists of, for each object x\in C, a collection K(x) of families of morphisms with codomain x, so that:
isomorphisms: for every isomorphism x\xrightarrow {f} y, \{f\}\in K(y);
stability: for every family \{x_i\xrightarrow {f_i}x\in K(x)\} and any map y\xrightarrow {g} x, there exists a family \{y_j\xrightarrow {h_j} y\}\in K(y) such that for each j, there exists an i and a map y_j\xrightarrow {k} x_i such that gh_j = f_ik;
transitivity: for every family \{x_i\xrightarrow {f_i}x\in K(x)\} and for every family of families \{x_{ij}\xrightarrow {g_{ij}} x_i\}\in K(x_i), the family of composites f_ig_{ij} is in K(x).

A Grothendieck topology J on a category C consists of, for each object x\in C, a collection of sieves on x J(x), called covering sieves, so that:
identity: the maximal sieve at x covers x;
stability: if S covers x and y\xrightarrow {f} x is any map, then the pullback sieve f^*S covers y;
transitivity: if S covers x and T is a sieve on x so that, for each map y\xrightarrow {f} x \in S, f^* T covers y, then T covers x.

Naturality is immediate from construction: both actions on maps y\xrightarrow {f}x
  simply pull back along f. To show that \chi _Q is classifying, we must
